segments.text: If it was local, I think it had to be, I don't know where people went.
Was Uncle Ed still going?
Uncle Ed, for that type of partying, which was usually just bowl sessions.
But yeah, Uncle Ed's was there until.
And none of those places that had been out near the air base during the war, those were.
Well, there was a, I was never, never went there.
There was something, it had the name Purple.
And it was between the, it was on 21 or within a block of Highway 21 somewhere.
But it was a pretty tough place.
That was my impression of it.
And there was a place there where wieners in Bryan there at Highway 21 and 6.
Now, there used to be something, a dance hall, one of these country western.
And that was a pretty popular place.
But

really uh we go there were these big drive-ins the texas drive-in down there where the chicken what's that dixie chicken dixie chicken yeah at the triangle at the triangle uh the texan and then and the triangle drive-in also there in the triangle and then there was another one in on down on highway six
in Bryan.
And those were popular hangout type places.
Did you, were y'all aware of a bootlegger in Brazos County?
I've not heard of anybody who was.
No, I knew of the Jones.
Whiskey Bridge.
Whiskey Bridge, uh-huh.
And that, that's one of the things, my first, I had my first, my introduction to wine.
when I was in summer school as a freshman after the bull ring one Saturday afternoon.
And it was really a scorcher.
This would have, it was the latter part of the summer.
And fished triple buzz boy Yarbrough from Mississippi.
He was, his dad owned a large hunk of Mississippi Delta.
And
He had an Oldsmobile 88.
And so he took us, he wanted to go out to Whiskey Bridge after the bull ring was finished, and we'd get something to drink.
He had a card fixed and everything.
And he got us, each one of us, a bottle, a chilled bottle of wine.
And it was sweet wine.
Tasted like, you know, tasted like chilled grape juice or fruit juice.
And sweet.
And boy, I was hot and thirsty.
And that was good.
And so I drank mine on the way back to town.
And I was through easy before we got back into town.
to the campus.
And that stuff hit me just as we were walking from the parking lot into the dorm.
And they said they essentially drug me to my bed, you know, and laid me out.
Now, as far as you recall, was there any checking in those days
to be sure that someone was 18 to buy whatever they were buying.
You just had to be ready, as I remember.
My impression was that it was pretty hit or miss.
I don't remember any checks or anything.
What were people smoking then?
Chesterfield cigarettes, Camel cigarettes, and Lucky Strikes were the big three.
And we had, there was a guy who, from Houston, who brought a cigarette rolling machine with him.
And so you could buy Bull Durham or Prince Albert and roll your own.
And he was very popular with the people that smoked.
I tried a few cigarettes.
that summer of my freshman year and in the fall I started smoking kind of on a spotty basis, but that's when I started smoking anyway.
About what percentage, reckon, of the students smoked then?
Oh.
It wasn't unusual.
There were quite a few
people smoked.
It was common to go into a room and at least one person be smoking.
And it was okay to smoke in the room.
Yeah.
You never thought about, not about asking anyone if you could smoke there.
What about pipes and cigars?
A few cigars, no pipes that I remember until, well, toward
the end of my vet school time, I began to notice some of the faculty and graduate students.
Chewing tobacco and snuff?
Not very often, but I don't remember any snuff, but some chewing tobacco.
Was that country?
Yeah, yeah.
And heroin and marijuana?
Didn't know anything about that.
Did you even know the words?
No.
That's right.
Did anybody ever drink a mixed drink?
Yeah, well...
Which to me meant putting something in a Coca-Cola.
Uh-huh, something like that.
Rum and Coca-Cola.
Or vodka.
Yeah.
This was a big thing at the big college dances in Chicago.
in Sabisa or one of the, you know, here on campus.
And people would go to elaborate means of concealing their bottle and take it into the, to Sabisa or wherever so they could have their mixed drinks.
How did Aggies, in fact, how did Aggies behave at those campus dances?
Well, most of them were very well behaved, I thought.
And how were the women treated?
Well, like queens.
Yeah, this was a very standard.
I mean, if a woman, a date was not treated that way, it was clearly the exception and just a very glaring happening for women.
for a date not to be treated very much like a princess.
Had you and your buddies heard about a chicken ranch at La Grange?
Did you know it existed?
Yeah, we knew of that, but I can't remember when I knew of that.
Was it while you were an undergraduate?
Yeah, but I can't remember how.
how long I'd been here, whenever I learned.
Did you hear of any Aggies going over there?
Well, yeah, you heard people talking about it, but you didn't know.
whether it was or is wishful thinking or whatever.
I have wondered if the stage version, which has a chicken ranch visit by Aggies as a part of being a part of the Corps, I wondered if that's been made up.
I haven't heard much about in all these interviews.
The Korean War was going on by this time.
Yeah.
What did you and your buddies, what were you all thinking about the war and what it might mean to you?
Well, this was a common discussion like in ROTC classes.
And a number of the core students during my sophomore year were, you know, they were really expecting to go and were looking forward to it.
I mean, and of course in squadrons, well, I think most of the squadrons had a fair number of students who envisioned themselves
the pilot of a fighter plane.
And the World War II vats were pretty well gone out of school by then.
And the large number of them.
They were just occasional ones.
And they were very low profile for almost always.
What was the status of the various extracurricular groups?
I'm assuming that the corps commander was the highest.
Yeah.
student on campus in terms of prestige.
What did y'all think about the band?
Well, it was held in high regard.
Were there jokes about the band or anything then?
Y'all didn't make fun of them?
What about Yale leaders?
Did they have high status?
Yeah, yeah.
What other student organizations were there with lots of credibility?
Well, Ross Volunteers, of course, were very highly regarded.
A lot of the various clubs were, you know, like the
FFA, Collegiate Chapter, that for in ag ed, you know, for that group of people, that was a really a pivotal organization.
The Agronomy Society.
So a lot of the discipline-oriented organizations were.
Did you get in one of those?
Was there a pre-vet club or group?
No, well, not to my knowledge.
I did not.
That came along later.
Were you aware of the existence of secret fraternities when you were a student?
I had heard of the TTs, but I didn't know really very much.
I didn't know any particulars about them.
Were you aware of anybody that supposedly was a member?
No.
Or what they supposedly did?
No.
All right, now during this sophomore year then, you're headed toward vet school.
When do you get, when do you apply and get admitted?
Well, make application in the spring after I came back down here.
I think it would have been probably like February, something around February.
And I,
It was after I came back down here that I went to the vet school.
That was the first time I was in the building that's been occupied by CE for so long.
The information I got actually was provided by
one of the staff in the dean's office.
But I did not see Dean Boughton.
See, he had his stroke, and so he was not available.
Fred Jagge, I remember being introduced to him as the interim dean, but I don't think he, I'm not sure he officially was that, but he functioned that way.
But,
I remember turning in my application there at the dean's office in the vet school.
As far as you were aware, what kind of academic requirements were there in terms of GPA and number of hours and so forth?
How hard was it going to be to get in?
Well, I had heard that it would probably take a B average
which at that time was a two-point field.

As it turned out, it didn't take that, but that was a scuttlebutt among my classmates, and I just wasn't sure whether I'd, because of my irregularities, you know, with the problem I had with that organic chemistry class and the low-grade intrigue,
I was very concerned about that.
Now another course that I had that was a first of its kind was physics.
I was in the first class of physics.
These were a new physics course that were presented, started my sophomore year, for

non-physics majors principally pre-vets and pre-meds and those type people and he was taught by the head of the department of physics dr potter we call him physics potter and that was quite an experience to me i i did okay in physics but if i'd if i'd had
if electricity had been a larger part of it, I think I probably would have flunked the course.
I could not get that down, get the concept down during the time I was in that course.
Dr. Potter, bless his heart, he really threw himself into the course, developing it.
And he wanted to make it relevant.
for the students who were taking.
He wanted all of us to enjoy and like physics.
That was his goal.
And so on the exams, since the majority of the students, I think, that were taking it that first year were pre-vet students, so he would write questions
He figured a pre-vet student would identify with and be interested in.
For example, on resistance, I remember he had a question.
His question had to do with, I think, gravity and maybe resistance.
Anyway, it was water swallowed by a giraffe.
And he had a question about an enraged bull, and I got tickled with that.
I'm sure I was feeling the pressure, but it just hit my funny bone, and I thought I wouldn't finish that exam every time I'd come to that question on that bull.
How long?
I'd just lose it.
After you applied for admission, how long before you heard the result?
Well, we were called in.
I don't know if everyone was interviewed, but I was called in for interview.
Describe the interview.
Oh, me, ooh, that was.
Who, how long, where?
Well, it was in the dean's office, and Dr. Boughton was back.
He was, had his cane.
B-O-U-G-H?
B-O-U, yeah.
T-O-N. Mm-hmm.
And Dr. John Miloff, Dr. Leonard, and Dr. Jaggi.
J-A-G-G-I.
Uh-huh.
As I remember those, I think that was it.
And was Boughton Miloff?
Yeah, there were four of them, I think.
Well, Dr. Bowden was sitting behind his desk over here.
I was sitting just inside the door.
And he was leaning back sort of like this, so he was very low profile physically.
And the other three, the three faculty members were sitting in chairs on,
this side so as the interview developed well they developed it you know asking for information from me and so on and they asked one of them asked if i knew what bai was and i

I had just heard or read about it not very long before Bureau of Animal Industries and so I said yes and they asked well what is it I told them it's a branch of the government and then the next question well tell us what it does and I was you know of course I was
wanting to really impress them with what I knew about it.
That's all I knew was that it was BAI branch of the government or federal agency.
As it turns out, see at that particular time, that was the branch of government in which disease control was being handled by veterinarians.
And so it was the agency you went to work for if you were a veterinarian.
I didn't know that.
So I just sat there trying to think, how do I answer this without sounding too stupid?
And I wasn't, I don't know how long it was silent.
The silence was broken by Dr. Boughton slamming his cane down on top of the desk.
And expletive, expletive, expletive.
You've got to answer things.
You've got to think on your feet.
That's what he said.
You've got to think on your feet, young man, if you want to be a veterinarian.
And boy, I don't remember any interview after that.
And it was over, fortunately, shortly after.
Half hour, hour?
Do you have any idea what the length was?
It would, I think on the order of a half hour probably.
And then how long before you heard the result of your application?
I think it was two or three weeks.
Phone call, letter, what?
How'd you?
Letter.
Letter.
Uh-huh.
Did you, what was your guess before you opened it?
What did you think the result was gonna be?
I figured I probably wasn't gonna get in after all of that.
And in those days they were admitting how many?
64, okay.
And did you?
I was in and probably,
I don't know what they did with the interviews.
I'm sure, talking with Dr. John in years after that, that they had no formal way for assigning a weight or anything.
You could probably just out and out disqualify yourself by doing something really stupid or weird, but I don't think
That little deficit on my part was probably, I just provided entertainment for the committee probably for the rest of the morning.
Did you do anything to celebrate?
Did you make any phone calls?
I called home.
What did mom and dad say?
They were very pleased.
And so then you go home that summer?
Yeah, I work in the oil field.
I'm really pretty motivated at that point.
And you come back then in the fall.
And the word had gotten around in Winters that I had been admitted to vet school.
I was going to be a veterinarian.
And that they had a rodeo in Winters that summer.
And not a very big one, but a local rodeo.
And in the course of events, they, in,
clearing one of the horses that a rider had who cleared the bulls out from the arena.
That horse was gored by a bull and his horn went in and just kind of went up a rib a little bit and opened up a pretty nasty looking wound.
So I was called with much fanfare and that was my first case.
trying to sew up that nasty wound.
Right.
Then you come back that fall.
Did you seek anybody's advice or counsel before coming back to vet school?
No.
I didn't know in Winters or in that area.
Well, there was a veterinarian in Ballinger by the name of Zedlitz, Dr. Zedlitz, but he was what to me was of such ancient years that anything he would have known wouldn't have been useful to me.
You were not really acquainted with a veterinarian, were you?
No, not there.
I had known a veterinarian, two veterinarians in Fisher County, and they had
observing them, a man by the name of Aldridge and a man by the name of Sweetwater and a young veterinarian by the name of Jones in row 10.
As you were at that point, what did you think you were going to do as a veterinarian?
I was going to large animal.
See, my decision, the reason I selected
veterinary medicine, I felt that that would provide me with a means of livelihood that would be sufficient that I could buy my own stock farm.
I wanted to have a stock farm or a ranch.
That was my goal.
In that area?
In the western part of the state, yeah.
Well, about west of here, I mean, central to west Texas.
So I was, my thought was probably, was mostly large animal, but I, or a general practice.
As far as you knew, did veterinarians make good income?
I thought they did, yeah.
It seemed to me that they were doing pretty well.
And the animals that you had cared for,
before that time were on your dad's property and a few pets?
Yeah, well, the pets were not of any significance.
I mean, we had dogs and a cat, but they were just dogs and cats.
I was close with the dogs, but I was very successful in high school

in swine production and i had a pretty i grew into a pretty sizable little herd of uh or drove of a registered duroc jersey pigs and started out with a sears pig out of the sears program and went on from there and uh so i i was a serious animal husband just when i was in high school i
See, when we lived in Brownwood, before I moved there, my orientation was largely in math.

And I accelerated, actually, in junior high school in the program they had in Brownwood and took so much of the math that when I got to Robie, I'd already had all the courses that they taught, that they offered.
So I went...
my junior and senior year in high school, I had no math, and that was part of my problem then when I hit that trig course.
I didn't have a, I'd been away from it a while.
When you get back that fall to begin vet school.
Uh-huh, I meet one,
Alvin A.
Price, among others.
Describe your first impressions of him.
Oh, he was about the slickest thing I'd ever seen.
That guy could talk, you know, boy, I mean, he was a lecturer and a half.
And very, very impressive.
He had a standard first lecture, which was a motivational lecture.
It's the sort of lecture that every vet school

every vet school needs a person to deliver that lecture and it's got to be a person though that's the teacher of the students in that first year and really set them straight what were the main major points in that speech well the uh he was exalting veterinary medicine as a profession and uh he he started out simply by

instructing us in the appropriate use of the word veterinarian versus veterinary and how to spell veterinarian six vowels and six consonants six syllables and except the way he said it you know it just registered all of my classmates to this day you know we mentioned in this room just to
four or five years ago when I had the class here, mentioned Al Price and they talk about veterinarian, six vowels, six consonants, six syllables.
But he was dressed impeccably, very energetic, a very energetic lecturer, very knowledgeable of his subjects.
And very demanding of you.
I mean, he did not want you to miss.
He wanted every I dotted, every T crossed.
That was the road to success.
And I went into his, well, attended his first lecture.
I don't remember in what attire, but I went to the first lab on Monday afternoon.
with him.
This was osteology lab where we worked with bones.
